she's gonna expose me ...
my name, my face, everything.

85
00:05:32,567 --> 00:05:34,000
Oh, my god. Okay...

86
00:05:34,034 --> 00:05:36,800
well, the h20 has
obviously gone to her head,

87
00:05:36,833 --> 00:05:38,867
and we need to figure out a way

88
00:05:38,900 --> 00:05:41,200
to kill that story once and for all.

89
00:05:41,234 --> 00:05:42,933
She's got a backup plan, chloe.

90
00:05:42,967 --> 00:05:44,467
Whether we stop her or not,

91
00:05:44,501 --> 00:05:46,534
she's still gonna release my identity.

92
00:05:48,601 --> 00:05:51,067
So i'm going public...

93
00:05:51,100 --> 00:05:52,900
<i>on my terms.</i>

94
00:05:52,933 --> 00:05:54,401
Whoa. Clark.

95
00:05:54,434 --> 00:05:56,768
Okay, i realize that after lana left,

96
00:05:56,800 --> 00:05:59,401
you really buried
yourself in patrol duty,

97
00:05:59,434 --> 00:06:01,401
and there's nothing wrong with that,

98
00:06:01,434 --> 00:06:04,434
but to come out waving the flag...

99
00:06:04,467 --> 00:06:06,301
i mean, that's huge.

100
00:06:06,334 --> 00:06:09,634
Chloe, i always thought that
i would live in secret forever.

101
00:06:09,668 --> 00:06:10,833
But you convinced me

102
00:06:10,867 --> 00:06:13,234
that jimmy's picture
of the red-blue blur

103
00:06:13,267 --> 00:06:16,768
was a symbol of hope.

104
00:06:16,800 --> 00:06:21,334
Didn't have an address
or a family or a face.

105
00:06:21,367 --> 00:06:22,634
I mean, are you sure

106
00:06:22,668 --> 00:06:25,367
that you're ready to have
all of your intimate details

107
00:06:25,401 --> 00:06:27,067
made into the banner headline?

108
00:06:27,100 --> 00:06:28,434
Well, i don't have a choice.

109
00:06:28,467 --> 00:06:29,734
At least this way,

110
00:06:29,768 --> 00:06:31,800
i can control the way my
story comes out in the press.

111
00:06:31,833 --> 00:06:32,100
Right, because the paparazzi

112
00:06:32,134 --> 00:06:33,334
e paparazzi

113
00:06:33,367 --> 00:06:36,167
are famous for respecting
people's privacy.

114
00:06:36,200 --> 00:06:37,867
Clark...

115
00:06:37,900 --> 00:06:40,301
<i>we can stop her. There's always a way.</i>

116
00:06:40,334 --> 00:06:42,134
No, chloe, this time is different.

117
00:06:42,167 --> 00:06:44,668
I mean, even if i agree
to be linda lake's puppet,

118
00:06:44,701 --> 00:06:47,367
eventually she will stab me
in the back and expose me.

119
00:06:47,401 --> 00:06:49,134
I need to stay one step ahead of her,

120
00:06:49,167 --> 00:06:50,967
not only for me but for
everyone else's sake.

121
00:06:52,867 --> 00:06:54,367
Even in a world this advanced,

122
00:06:54,401 --> 00:06:56,000
people are still pretty backwards

123
00:06:56,034 --> 00:06:57,668
when it comes to accepting change.

124
00:06:57,701 --> 00:07:00,000
I know, chloe, but when
the red and blue blur

125
00:07:00,034 --> 00:07:03,200
hit the front page, people accepted it.

126
00:07:03,234 --> 00:07:05,734
And maybe they're ready to accept me.

127
00:07:07,933 --> 00:07:10,501
There could be an upside
to all this, you know.

128
00:07:10,534 --> 00:07:12,334
For the first time in my life,

129
00:07:12,367 --> 00:07:16,100
i may actually be able to be myself.

130
00:07:29,833 --> 00:07:31,100
Can i ask you what you're doing?

131
00:07:32,768 --> 00:07:35,933
Davis bloome ... i'm
one of the, uh, emts.

132
00:07:35,967 --> 00:07:37,768
I've never seen you before.

133
00:07:37,800 --> 00:07:40,267
Well, i've been out for a few weeks.

134
00:07:40,301 --> 00:07:42,301
Do you want to explain this?

135
00:07:46,234 --> 00:07:48,034
I'm just restocking my rig.

136
00:07:48,067 --> 00:07:52,200
Antipsychotics used for
multiple personalties.

137
00:07:52,234 --> 00:07:55,434
Yeah, not exactly your
latest designer drug, is it?

138
00:07:58,867 --> 00:08:00,334
I'm sorry.

139
00:08:00,367 --> 00:08:03,000
I hope whoever it's for,
they get the help they need.

140
00:08:03,034 --> 00:08:04,301
Trust me, so do i.

141
00:08:22,768 --> 00:08:25,234
Can i talk to you?

142
00:08:25,267 --> 00:08:27,401
Wow. What is that noise?

143
00:08:27,434 --> 00:08:29,000
Is someone talking?

144
00:08:29,034 --> 00:08:31,367
Lois, you can't ignore me forever.

145
00:08:31,401 --> 00:08:32,467
Could be worse ...

146
00:08:32,501 --> 00:08:34,734
you could be ignored in
a three-hour downpour.

147
00:08:36,800 --> 00:08:38,701
I want you to write my story.

148
00:08:40,401 --> 00:08:42,334
No offense, but i've
long since graduated

149
00:08:42,367 --> 00:08:44,601
from the "lonely seeking
lonely" or classifieds.

150
00:08:44,634 --> 00:08:46,134
It's a pretty interesting one.

151
00:08:46,167 --> 00:08:47,768
Clark, i'm busy here.

152
00:08:47,800 --> 00:08:50,534
You may have forgotten about
me, but the news world didn't.

153
00:08:50,567 --> 00:08:53,100
After the story you're about
to write, it never will.

154
00:08:53,134 --> 00:08:54,534
What story?

155
00:08:54,567 --> 00:08:58,534
I didn't forget to pick
you up at the airport, lois.

156
00:08:58,567 --> 00:09:00,167
The reason i wasn't there

157
00:09:00,200 --> 00:09:02,534
is because i was protecting people.

158
00:09:06,267 --> 00:09:08,267
I'm the red-blue blur.

159
00:09:14,334 --> 00:09:15,967
That's the best you can do?

160
00:09:18,668 --> 00:09:20,933
That thing that saved
you from the speeding car,

161
00:09:20,967 --> 00:09:22,000
that was me.

162
00:09:22,034 --> 00:09:23,800
That time the barn door
flew off its hinges,

163
00:09:23,833 --> 00:09:25,301
you thought it was a weather anomaly.

164
00:09:25,334 --> 00:09:26,334
I did that.

165
00:09:26,367 --> 00:09:28,800
Yeah, right. What'd you do ...  sneeze?

166
00:09:28,833 --> 00:09:30,467
Actually...

167
00:09:30,501 --> 00:09:32,668
clark, next time you liquid-lunch,

168
00:09:32,701 --> 00:09:34,601
take the rest of the day off.

169
00:09:37,567 --> 00:09:39,200
Let me help you with that.

170
00:10:01,534 --> 00:10:04,668
Guess i should stop
calling you "smallville."

171
00:10:24,234 --> 00:10:26,834
You're speechless.
That's never a good thing.

172
00:10:28,901 --> 00:10:32,301
The disappearing acts,
the half-baked excuses...

173
00:10:32,334 --> 00:10:35,334
all this time, i just coughed it up

174
00:10:35,368 --> 00:10:38,734
to a classic case of
peter pan syndrome, but...

175
00:10:41,533 --> 00:10:43,901
...you're the opposite.

176
00:10:43,934 --> 00:10:45,600
You're like...

177
00:10:48,667 --> 00:10:49,967
...a hero?

178
00:10:50,001 --> 00:10:55,001
Look, lois, this is a lot to take in...

179
00:10:55,034 --> 00:10:57,700
all at once, but i wanted
you to hear it from me

180
00:10:57,734 --> 00:10:59,901
before you heard it from anyone else.

181
00:10:59,934 --> 00:11:02,268
So, why am i the first one you told?

182
00:11:04,134 --> 00:11:05,967
Actually, lois, you're not.

183
00:11:09,433 --> 00:11:11,433
Lana and chloe already know.

184
00:11:13,268 --> 00:11:15,600
Someone's had a busy morning.

185
00:11:17,301 --> 00:11:19,134
They've known for years.

186
00:11:22,700 --> 00:11:25,634
Right. Of course.

187
00:11:28,500 --> 00:11:31,167
Start at the beginning.

188
00:11:34,667 --> 00:11:36,467
What guns you got in your arsenal?

189
00:11:39,334 --> 00:11:42,533
Guess i might as well just
throw it all out there.

190
00:11:42,567 --> 00:11:44,834
I can blast fire out of my eyes.

191
00:11:48,767 --> 00:11:50,600
Okay.

192
00:11:52,767 --> 00:11:55,034
I can hear a dog barking
from 10 miles away.

193
00:11:55,067 --> 00:11:56,800
I can see through solid objects,

194
00:11:56,834 --> 00:11:59,134
and i can run faster
than the speed of sound.

195
00:11:59,167 --> 00:12:00,400
Wait.

196
00:12:00,433 --> 00:12:02,767
Rewind.

197
00:12:04,533 --> 00:12:07,067
Expand on your whole...

198
00:12:07,101 --> 00:12:10,067
"see through things" thing.

199
00:12:10,101 --> 00:12:12,368
No, lo...  i...

200
00:12:12,400 --> 00:12:14,867
look, i have to focus.

201
00:12:18,800 --> 00:12:21,368
How did i not put these pieces together?

202
00:12:21,400 --> 00:12:23,268
I mean, i lived with you,

203
00:12:23,301 --> 00:12:26,301
and now we practically
work on top of each other.

204
00:12:26,334 --> 00:12:29,034
I mean, have i been
high this entire time?

205
00:12:31,734 --> 00:12:35,700
The important thing
is that you know now.

206
00:12:35,734 --> 00:12:39,134
And there's no better reporter
to tell my story than you.

207
00:12:41,533 --> 00:12:43,667
Would you do me the honor?

208
00:12:45,901 --> 00:12:47,500
Consider it done.

209
00:12:47,533 --> 00:12:51,167
Tomorrow's front page will tell the tale

210
00:12:51,201 --> 00:12:55,001
of the red-and-blue,
meteor-infected hero.

211
00:12:56,734 --> 00:12:58,734
About the meteors...

212
00:13:01,334 --> 00:13:04,400
we should talk about where i'm from.

213
00:13:22,967 --> 00:13:24,800
Your money's no good here.

214
00:13:24,834 --> 00:13:25,934
For 50 years,

215
00:13:25,967 --> 00:13:28,533
i've watched this city
get eaten alive by crime.

216
00:13:28,567 --> 00:13:30,433
But you picked us up, kent.

217
00:13:30,467 --> 00:13:35,834
You reminded everybody what
it means to be good again.

218
00:13:35,867 --> 00:13:38,567
Excuse me, mr. Kent.

219
00:13:38,600 --> 00:13:40,533
Can i get your autograph?

220
00:13:42,101 --> 00:13:43,567
Sure.

221
00:13:46,767 --> 00:13:47,901
There you go.

222
00:13:47,934 --> 00:13:50,734
I like your outfit.

223
00:13:52,301 --> 00:13:54,400
Thanks!

224
00:13:58,201 --> 00:13:59,600
He's so dreamy!

225
00:13:59,634 --> 00:14:00,767
Oh, my god!

226
00:14:00,800 --> 00:14:02,600
Wow, red-blue blur.

227
00:14:02,634 --> 00:14:04,533
Oh, i want his autograph!

228
00:14:04,567 --> 00:14:06,034
All right!

229
00:14:06,067 --> 00:14:07,967
He is sexy! That guy?

230
00:14:15,867 --> 00:14:19,134
Hey, clark! Catch!

231
00:14:22,901 --> 00:14:24,567
I'll fall for you any day, clark.

232
00:14:24,600 --> 00:14:26,467
You can't just do that.

233
00:14:26,500 --> 00:14:27,800
It's not...

234
00:14:27,834 --> 00:14:28,834
that's clark!

235
00:14:28,867 --> 00:14:31,167
No way! You guys see that?!

236
00:14:34,368 --> 00:14:38,667
You may have scooped me, but
i will have the last word.

237
00:14:55,167 --> 00:14:56,201
You don't understand.

238
00:14:56,234 --> 00:14:57,934
There has to be a room available.

239
00:14:57,967 --> 00:14:59,934
My husband's being transferred here now.

240
00:14:59,967 --> 00:15:01,201
I confirmed yesterday.

241
00:15:01,234 --> 00:15:04,101
Yesterday, our parking lots
weren't full of paparazzis,

242
00:15:04,134 --> 00:15:06,500
and our hallways weren't
full of rubbernecking fans.

243
00:15:06,533 --> 00:15:08,234
